---
requires:
  - arbiter-core
import:
  - typescript-react-app-template
description: >-
  Arbiter web app: fetches real London billboard inventory, runs a live
  multi-round auction with Claude-backed advertiser agents, and renders a 3D
  scene plus an auditable per-agent scorecard. All money figures come from
  arbiter-core; the app only displays them.
---

***definitions***

- :OverpassQuery: is the request sent to the OpenStreetMap Overpass API.
  - It asks for advertising billboards inside the London bounding box.

- :PricingModel: turns a raw billboard's area into a deterministic, documented basePrice and bidIncrement.
  - It produces the pricing for a :BillboardSlot:.
  - It is a transparent function of the billboard, not a live market rate.

- :InventorySource: fetches real London billboards through :OverpassQuery:.
  - It normalises each into a :BillboardSlot: using :PricingModel:, and caches the first fetch.

- :BidDecision: is one agent's choice for one contested slot in one round.
  - The choice is raise, hold, or drop, plus the raise amount when raising.

- :AgentRuntime: wraps one :AdvertiserAgent: as a live bidder.
  - Given the public auction state it returns a :BidDecision: per contested slot it wants.
  - It never returns an action that exceeds the agent's remaining budget.

- :RoundEvent: is a streamed snapshot of one round.
  - It carries the round number, the standing bid per contested slot, the drop-outs so far, and remaining budgets.

- :ArenaOrchestrator: runs the auction.
  - It drives synchronized rounds and collects a :BidDecision: from each :AgentRuntime:.
  - It appends the resulting valid :Bid: and :DropOut: events to an :AuctionLog: and advances until every slot clears.
  - When the auction ends it calls :ClearingEngine: then :Referee: to produce the final results.

- :RoundStream: is the channel that pushes each :RoundEvent: to the browser as the auction runs.

- :LondonMapScene: is a full-viewport Mapbox 3D map of London with a deck.gl overlay for the auction.
  - The map is centred on London and pitched so the buildings read as 3D.
  - The deck.gl overlay draws one 3D column per :BillboardSlot: plus the live :BidEdge: arcs.

- :AgentAnchor: is a fixed position on the map assigned to one :AdvertiserAgent:.
  - It is the fixed origin point for that agent's bid arcs.

- :BidEdge: is a short-lived deck.gl arc drawn from a bidding agent's :AgentAnchor: to the slot it bid on.

- :ClearingPulse: is the visual settling that plays when a :ClearingResult: arrives.
  - It locks each slot's column to its winner's colour and final price.

- :ScorecardPanel: is the per-agent panel that displays an :AgentScorecard: exactly as arbiter-core produced it.

- :AuctionHUD: is the round ticker overlay.
  - It shows the current round, the standing bid per contested slot, and remaining budgets.

- :MiniMap: is a small 2D top-down overview map inset over :LondonMapScene:.
  - It orients the user by showing where the main map is centred, with a marker at that centre.

***implementation reqs***

- :InventorySource: fetches from the public OpenStreetMap Overpass API, which needs no API key.
  - The Overpass endpoint defaults to the runtime value `https://overpass-api.de/api/interpreter`, overridable by env.
  - The London bounding box is south 51.28, west -0.51, north 51.70, east 0.33.
  - The first fetch is live; its normalised result is written to the cache file `public/cache/london_inventory.json`.
  - Later runs read that cache file instead of calling Overpass again.
- :PricingModel: computes basePrice as a documented function of the billboard's estimated face area in square metres.
  - basePrice = 50 pounds plus 25 pounds per square metre of face area, rounded to the nearest whole pound.
  - When area is unknown, a default face area of 12 square metres is assumed.
  - bidIncrement = 10 percent of basePrice, rounded to the nearest whole pound, with a floor of 5 pounds.
  - This formula is presented to the user as a transparent estimate, never as a live market rate.
- :AgentRuntime: makes its bidding decisions with the Claude API, one call per agent per decision.
  - The default model is `claude-sonnet-4-6`, overridable by env; the API key is read from env `VITE_ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`.
  - Each agent's prompt is private: it contains only that agent's own budget, its own per-slot valuation, and its goal.
  - One agent's valuation is never placed in another agent's prompt.
- :ArenaOrchestrator: depends on the :AgentRuntime: decision contract, not on the Claude API directly.
  - This lets tests inject a deterministic :AgentRuntime: while production wires the Claude-backed one.
- :ArenaOrchestrator: ends the auction when the count of cleared slots equals the total number of slots in the auction.
  - The total number of slots is the element count (length) of the ordered slot list, not the size of any set or map.
  - The round loop keeps running while strictly fewer slots have cleared than that total slot count.
- The deterministic auction maths is delegated entirely to arbiter-core, imported from `src/core/`.
  - The app never recomputes a cleared price, fair price, overpayment, surplus, or left-on-table value.
- :RoundStream: pushes :RoundEvent: updates over a WebSocket; a Server-Sent-Events channel is an acceptable fallback.
- The default auction runs with 4 advertiser agents over the London inventory.
- Each :AdvertiserAgent: gets a fixed display colour by its index in the agent list, from a shared four-colour palette.
  - The palette, in order, is blue #3B82F6, red #EF4444, green #22C55E, and amber #EAB308.
  - The exact same palette constant is used by both the implementation and its tests, so asserted colours always match.
  - The same colour is used for that agent's :AgentAnchor:, :BidEdge:, :ClearingPulse:, and :ScorecardPanel:.
- The map scene always fills the browser viewport and resizes with the window.
- The 3D London map is the full-screen background; all panels float over it as glassmorphism cards.
  - Glassmorphism means a translucent dark fill with a backdrop blur (frosted glass), a subtle light 1px border,
    rounded corners, and a soft drop shadow.
  - Panel text is high-contrast and legible over the map — light text with enough weight and spacing to read easily.
  - Floating panels never cover the whole map; the map stays the main, visible surface behind them.
- App :UnitTests: that start an auction assert the settled end state, not the transient "in progress" label.
  - A deterministic auction completes inside the start handler, so the in-progress label is not reliably observable.
  - After starting, assert that one :ScorecardPanel: per agent is shown and the start control is no longer offered.

***test reqs***
- :ConformanceTests: for the map scene mock `mapbox-gl` and deck.gl.
  - They never instantiate a real Mapbox map or GPU context, and run under jsdom.
  - They assert on the scene configuration and the overlay layer data, not on real WebGL rendering.
- :ConformanceTests: for :AgentRuntime: selection use `vi.stubEnv` for the env and `vi.stubGlobal` for global `fetch`.
  - For the Claude path: stub `VITE_ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` and mock `fetch` to resolve a JSON body with a `content` array.
  - For the deterministic path: leave the key unset and assert `fetch` is never called.
  - The deterministic path is tested with plain calls — no env or network mocking is needed for its decision logic.
  - A test that drives a full auction to verify the Claude path awaits the async run before asserting `fetch` ran.
    - The Claude-backed :AgentRuntime: issues its `fetch` calls asynchronously while the auction runs.
- :ConformanceTests: for the scorecard click-to-explain view use a :ClearingResult: whose audit trail is non-empty.
  - With audit events present, the explanation lists them rather than showing the empty 'no events recorded' state.

***functional specs***

- Implement the Arbiter app entry point.
  - `index.html` loads `src/main.tsx`, which mounts the root React component into the `#root` element.
  - The root component shows an empty London stage and a control to start an auction.
  - Running `npm run dev` serves the app on Vite's dev server.

- Implement :PricingModel: as a stateless component that derives slot pricing from a billboard.
  - It exposes one operation that takes a billboard's face area in square metres.
  - It returns basePrice and bidIncrement.
  - It applies the documented pricing formula, assuming the default face area when area is missing.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - A billboard with a face area of 12 square metres yields basePrice 350 and bidIncrement 35.

- Implement :InventorySource: fetching and normalisation from :OverpassQuery:.
  - It queries the Overpass endpoint for advertising billboards within the London bounding box.
  - It normalises each returned element into a :BillboardSlot:.
    - Each :BillboardSlot: gets a stable id, a name, a latitude, a longitude, and pricing from :PricingModel:.
  - It returns the list of normalised :BillboardSlot: items.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - A fetch returns at least one normalised :BillboardSlot:.
  - Every returned slot has a latitude within 51.28 to 51.70 and a longitude within -0.51 to 0.33.

- Implement :InventorySource: caching so only the first fetch is live.
  - On the first call, after a successful live fetch, the normalised slots are written to the cache file.
  - On any later call, the slots are read from that cache file and no Overpass request is made.
  - The cached set is identical to the set returned by the first fetch.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - Calling :InventorySource: a second time returns the same set of :BillboardSlot: items as the first call.
  - The second call issues no network request.

- Implement the :AgentRuntime: decision contract and its budget enforcement.
  - :AgentRuntime: exposes one operation: given the public auction state, return a :BidDecision: per wanted slot.
  - A raise :BidDecision: whose amount would exceed the agent's remaining budget is rejected and downgraded to a drop.
    - So the runtime never emits an over-budget action.
  - The contract is satisfiable by a deterministic implementation for testing, independent of any Claude call.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - Take an :AgentRuntime: for an agent with remaining budget 120, asked to act where a valid raise would be 130.
  - It never returns a raise; it returns a drop or hold, and the rejected over-budget raise is recorded as the reason.

- Implement the Claude-backed :AgentRuntime: that produces live :BidDecision: values.
  - For each decision it makes one Claude API call with the agent's private prompt.
    - The private prompt holds the agent's budget, its per-slot valuation, and its goal.
  - It parses the model reply into a :BidDecision: per slot, then applies the budget guard from the prior spec.
  - A malformed or missing reply is treated as a hold for that slot.

- Implement the :ArenaOrchestrator: round loop that runs a full headless auction to completion.
  - Every agent is a contender for a slot until it drops out of that slot.
    - A contender that has not yet bid still counts as a contender.
    - A slot is contested while two or more contenders remain on it.
    - A slot clears when exactly one contender remains; that contender is the winner.
    - The slot is NOT settled merely because only one agent has bid so far — others may still enter.
  - Within a round the orchestrator processes agents one at a time in a fixed order.
    - It asks each agent for its :BidDecision: from the live state.
    - The live state already reflects every :Bid: and :DropOut: made earlier in the same round.
  - On a slot with no standing bid yet, a contender enters by bidding at least the slot basePrice.
  - A slot's winner always has its own opening :Bid: recorded in the :AuctionLog: before that slot clears.
    - The opening :Bid: is at least the slot basePrice, so :ClearingEngine: prices an uncontested win at basePrice.
    - This holds even for a sole contender — the slot never clears as one that nobody bid on.
  - On a slot that already has a standing bid, a non-leading contender does one of:
    - raise to at least the standing bid plus the slot bidIncrement, becoming the new leader; or
    - drop out, recording priceAtDropOut as the standing bid it declined to beat; or
    - hold, taking no action this round while staying a contender.
  - The current leader of a slot takes no action that round and stays a contender.
  - A non-leading contender that holds stays a contender; a slot does not clear just because non-leaders are waiting.
  - The loop advances rounds until every slot has cleared, then stops.
  - A round is a stall on a contested slot when that round completes with no raise and no drop-out on that slot.
    - On a stalled contested slot the slot resolves at once: the current leader becomes the winner at the standing bid.
    - Each other remaining contender on the slot is recorded as a :DropOut: at that standing bid (its priceAtDropOut).
  - Termination is guaranteed even when agents hold.
    - Each round either changes a contested slot through a raise or a drop-out, or the stall rule resolves it.
    - So every contested slot strictly progresses until it clears; an agent that cannot afford a raise drops out.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - A headless single-slot run with two deterministic agents, where one keeps raising and the other drops once the price
    passes its limit, terminates with the slot cleared and exactly one winner.
  - In that run the losing agent appears in the :AuctionLog: with a drop-out, proving the slot was genuinely contested.
  - The resulting :AuctionLog: passes :AuctionValidator: with no violations.

- Implement :ArenaOrchestrator: final scoring once the auction ends.
  - It calls :ClearingEngine: on the completed :AuctionLog: to get a :ClearingResult: per slot.
  - It then calls :Referee: with the results, the log, and the agents to get one :AgentScorecard: per agent.
  - It returns a final bundle of the slots, the :AuctionLog:, the clearing results, and the scorecards.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - After a headless run, the final bundle has one :ClearingResult: per slot and one :AgentScorecard: per agent.
  - For every agent, the bundle's :AgentScorecard: equals :Referee: run directly on the bundle's own :AuctionLog: and
    clearing results — proving the orchestrator only relays core output and never recomputes it.

- Implement :RoundEvent: streaming through :RoundStream:.
  - As the orchestrator finishes each round it emits a :RoundEvent:.
    - The :RoundEvent: holds the round number, the standing bid per contested slot, the drop-outs so far, and budgets.
  - :RoundStream: pushes each :RoundEvent: to connected clients over a WebSocket, with a Server-Sent-Events fallback.
  - The browser receives the rounds in order.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - A three-round contested auction emits exactly three :RoundEvent: messages, one per round, in round order.
    - Construct the run with two competing agents that raise against each other for three rounds before one drops.
    - A single-agent slot clears in its first round and cannot stand in for a three-round auction.
  - Each message carries the standing bid for every still-contested slot.

- Implement :LondonMapScene: as a full-viewport Mapbox 3D map of London.
  - It mounts a Mapbox map that fills the viewport, using the Mapbox Standard style `mapbox://styles/mapbox/standard`.
    - That style renders extruded 3D buildings.
    - The Mapbox access token comes from `VITE_MAPBOX_TOKEN`.
  - Once the style loads, the map sets its basemap config to the "faded" theme and the "night" light preset.
    - Concretely it calls the map's config setter for `basemap` `theme` to `faded` and `lightPreset` to `night`.
    - This gives a dark, subtly-coloured night map so the auction visuals stand out.
  - The initial camera is centred on central London at zoom 15.5 with a pitch of 60 degrees.
    - The high pitch keeps the camera close to the ground so the 3D buildings read clearly, not a top-down view.
  - A deck.gl overlay is layered on top of the map for the auction visuals, sharing the map camera.
  - The map resizes to stay full-viewport when the window changes size.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - :LondonMapScene: uses the Standard style with the "faded" theme and the "night" light preset.
  - The camera is centred on central London at zoom 15.5 with pitch 60, and a deck.gl overlay is mounted over the map.
  - When the window resizes, the map stays full-viewport.

- Implement :BillboardSlot: columns on the :LondonMapScene: overlay.
  - The deck.gl overlay draws one 3D column per :BillboardSlot:, positioned at the slot's longitude and latitude.
  - Each column's height and colour scale with the slot's current value.
  - The number of columns always equals the number of slots in the auction.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - For an auction of 6 slots, the column layer has exactly 6 data entries, each at its slot's longitude and latitude.
  - A slot with a higher current value produces a taller column than a slot with a lower value.

- Implement :BidEdge: arcs driven by bids.
  - Each :AdvertiserAgent: is assigned a fixed :AgentAnchor: position on the map.
  - When a :Bid: occurs in a :RoundEvent:, the overlay draws a deck.gl arc from the agent's :AgentAnchor: to the slot.
  - Each :BidEdge: arc fades out shortly after it appears, so only recent bids are shown.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - A round with two distinct bids yields an arc layer holding two arcs.
  - Each arc starts at the bidding agent's :AgentAnchor: and ends at the bid slot's longitude and latitude.

- Implement :AuctionHUD: as the round ticker overlay.
  - It shows the current round number, the standing bid for each contested slot, and every agent's remaining budget.
  - It updates on each incoming :RoundEvent:.
  - The :AuctionHUD: is a glassmorphism panel floating in a corner over the map, not a solid bar.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - When a :RoundEvent: for round 3 arrives with two contested slots, the :AuctionHUD: shows round 3.
  - It also shows both slots' standing bids and all agents' remaining budgets.

- Implement :ClearingPulse: triggered by clearing results.
  - When the :ClearingResult: for a slot arrives, its column plays a settling pulse and locks to the winner's colour.
  - The column then shows the slot's final clearingPrice taken verbatim from the :ClearingResult:.
  - The displayed winner and price are never recomputed in the app.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - For scenario S1 cleared by arbiter-core, the slot's column locks to agent A's colour and displays the price 140.
  - The displayed values match the :ClearingResult: exactly, with no recomputation in the app.

- Implement :ScorecardPanel: displaying each :AgentScorecard:.
  - For every agent it shows surplusCaptured, overpayment, leftOnTable, and the concessionErrors with their reasons.
  - Every money figure is taken verbatim from the :AgentScorecard:; the app performs no arithmetic on these numbers.
  - Each :ScorecardPanel: is a glassmorphism card.
    - The cards float in a vertical stack along one side of the screen, over the 3D map, not on an opaque page.
    - Each card is headed by its agent and tints to that agent's colour, with the money figures shown large and legible.
    - The map stays the main, visible background behind the floating cards.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - For scenario S1, agent A's :ScorecardPanel: shows the exact core figures: overpayment 10, surplusCaptured 40.
  - The panel lists the overbid-while-uncontested concession error.
  - The scorecards render as frosted glassmorphism cards floating over the map, not as an opaque full-screen panel.

- Implement click-to-explain in :ScorecardPanel:.
  - Clicking any money figure on a scorecard reveals the exact :AuctionEvent: items it was computed from.
    - Those events come from the :ClearingResult: auditTrail and the :AuctionLog:.
  - The explanation lists those events only; it never derives a new number.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - For scenario S1, clicking agent A's overpayment of 10 reveals the audit-trail events behind it.
  - Those events show the drop-out at 130 and the raise to 140 that the overpayment was derived from.

- Extend :ArenaOrchestrator: so a caller can watch the auction round by round.
  - The run accepts an optional round listener.
  - After each completed round, the orchestrator emits a :RoundEvent: to the listener.
    - The :RoundEvent: carries the round number, the standing bid per contested slot, the drop-outs so far, and budgets.
  - The orchestrator still returns the same final bundle when the auction ends.
  - Running without a listener behaves exactly as before — the listener is optional and changes no auction outcome.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - A headless three-round deterministic auction run with a listener calls the listener three times, in round order.
  - Each emitted :RoundEvent: carries the standing bid for every still-contested slot.
  - The final bundle returned by the run is identical whether or not a listener was supplied.

- Add a deterministic :AgentRuntime: and wire the Claude-backed one for in-browser use.
  - Configure the Claude-backed :AgentRuntime: to read its key from `VITE_ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`.
    - The Claude bidding strategy uses model `claude-sonnet-4-6` as its default model.
    - Every Claude request sends `claude-sonnet-4-6`, including runtimes the selector builds with no explicit model.
    - Its request sends the header `anthropic-dangerous-direct-browser-access` set to `true`.
      - That header lets the call run from a browser.
  - Provide a separate deterministic :AgentRuntime: that needs no network and decides per contested slot:
    - if the agent is the current leader, hold;
    - else if a one-increment raise stays within the agent's valuation and budget, raise by one increment;
    - else drop out.
  - Provide a selector that returns the Claude-backed :AgentRuntime: when `VITE_ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` is set.
    - The selector returns the deterministic :AgentRuntime: when the key is absent.
  - With no key set, a full auction runs on the deterministic :AgentRuntime: and makes no network call.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - With no `VITE_ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` present, the selector returns the deterministic :AgentRuntime:.
  - That runtime returns only valid, non-over-budget :BidDecision: values and makes no network request.
  - With a key present, the :AgentRuntime: the selector builds sends model `claude-sonnet-4-6` in its Claude request.
  - A full headless auction of four deterministic agents over one slot terminates with the slot cleared and a valid
    :AuctionLog:.

- Wire the live auction into the app entry point so clicking start runs and shows a full auction.
  - :LondonMapScene: fills the whole screen as the background; the :AuctionHUD: and :ScorecardPanel: float over it.
    - The scorecards float as a vertical stack along one side; the map stays the main, visible surface.
  - When the user clicks the start control, the app loads inventory through :InventorySource: and shows the resulting
    :BillboardSlot: items as columns on :LondonMapScene:.
  - It creates 4 :AdvertiserAgent: items, each with a budget and a private per-slot valuation.
    - Each agent is wrapped as an :AgentRuntime: chosen by the selector.
      - The selector gives the Claude-backed runtime when a key is set, otherwise the deterministic one.
  - It runs :ArenaOrchestrator: with a round listener.
    - Each :RoundEvent: updates :AuctionHUD: and triggers :BidEdge: animations on :LondonMapScene:.
  - When the auction ends, it plays :ClearingPulse: on each slot and shows one :ScorecardPanel: per agent.
  - While an auction is running, the start control shows a running state and cannot launch a second auction.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - Starting the app with inventory and agents supplied by deterministic fallbacks loads the slots onto :LondonMapScene:
    and, when the run finishes, renders exactly one :ScorecardPanel: per agent populated from the final bundle.
  - The money figures shown on each :ScorecardPanel: equal the bundle's :AgentScorecard: values, with no recomputation.

- Refine the :LondonMapScene: camera to open close to the ground, ideally at the viewer's own location.
  - The initial camera keeps its existing centre on central London and its existing pitch of 60 degrees unchanged.
    - Only the initial zoom changes: it opens at zoom 19, right down among the buildings rather than high above them.
    - Leaving the central-London centre and the 60-degree pitch untouched preserves the existing initial-view contract.
  - When the scene mounts it asks the browser for the viewer's geolocation exactly once, and only if that API exists.
    - If a position is granted and it falls inside the London bounding box, the camera flies to it at zoom 19, pitch 60.
    - If geolocation is missing, denied, errors, or lands outside London, the camera simply stays on central London.
  - The fly-in is a smooth animated camera move on the already-mounted map.
    - It never changes the initial centre, pitch, or the configured initial zoom values the scene was created with.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - With geolocation unavailable or denied, the scene still mounts centred on central London at pitch 60 and zoom 19,
    and issues no camera move to anywhere outside London.

- Refine the billboard visuals so each :BillboardSlot: reads as a sign fixed to its building, not a floating cylinder.
  - The primary slot layer keeps its existing layer identifier and exactly one entry per :BillboardSlot:.
    - So the number of slot markers always equals the slot count, and each entry still carries its own slot identity.
  - Each slot is drawn as a compact, flat billboard marker pinned at the slot's longitude and latitude.
    - The marker is raised to roughly rooftop height so it sits against the building at that point.
    - It reads as a small sign on a thin post, never as a wide extruded column rising from the street.
  - The building location is highlighted so the eye is drawn to it.
    - A soft glowing halo is drawn at the slot's position, sized and brightened by the slot's current value.
    - A higher-valued slot is shown more prominently than a lower-valued one.
  - The marker and its highlight follow the existing colour rules.
    - A slot that has cleared locks to its winning agent's colour, exactly as the clearing visuals already do.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - For an auction of 6 slots, the primary slot layer holds exactly 6 entries, one at each slot's longitude and
    latitude, and a higher-valued slot renders more prominently than a lower-valued one.

- Refine every floating panel over :LondonMapScene: into a lighter, true liquid-glass material so the map shows through.
  - This applies to the title-and-control panel, the :AuctionHUD:, and each :ScorecardPanel:.
  - Each panel's fill becomes far more translucent than before — only about a quarter to a third opaque.
    - The 3D map and its buildings stay clearly visible through the glass.
  - The frosted effect is stronger: a larger background blur combined with boosted saturation of what sits behind it.
    - This gives the bright, wet 'liquid glass' look rather than a flat dark slab.
  - Each panel gains a thin bright hairline border and a soft light sheen along its top edge, over a layered shadow.
    - Corners stay generously rounded.
  - Text stays high-contrast and fully legible: light text with enough weight, size, and contrast to read over the map.
  - Only the glass material changes; every panel's content, layout, figures, and agent colours stay exactly as they are.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - The control panel, the :AuctionHUD:, and a :ScorecardPanel: each still display their existing content while
    rendering as a translucent, blurred, hairline-bordered glass card that the map is visible through.

- Bound the live auction to a map-centred subset of inventory so the scene and the round loop stay smooth.
  - :InventorySource: still fetches and returns the full normalised set; nothing about its own contract changes.
  - The cap is applied where the auction is started, not inside :InventorySource:.
    - When starting an auction, the app keeps only the :BillboardSlot: items closest to central London.
    - Closeness is the plain distance from central London to each slot's longitude and latitude.
    - It keeps at most a fixed maximum number of slots, default 24, held as a single named constant so it is easy to tune.
  - Only the kept slots are drawn as markers and entered into :ArenaOrchestrator:; the rest are not shown or auctioned.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - Starting an auction over an inventory of more than 24 slots runs :ArenaOrchestrator: over exactly the 24 slots
    closest to central London, and the scene shows exactly those 24 as markers.

- Fix :LondonMapScene: so the Mapbox map loads its tiles and stays smooth at every zoom and pan.
  - The night light preset and faded theme configuration must be applied to the map exactly once, and it must stick.
    - It is applied at the first style event where the map reports its style is FULLY loaded — that is, where the
      map's own "is the style loaded" check returns true — not merely when the style's layers first appear.
      - Applying it before the style is fully loaded silently fails, leaving the map on its default day theme.
    - After it has been applied successfully one time, a guard remembered across re-renders skips it forever after.
  - This is critical: re-applying the style configuration on every style-update event makes the Mapbox Standard style
    re-configure itself, which emits another style-update event, which re-applies it again — an endless loop.
    - While that loop runs, the style never reaches a loaded state, so the map never requests or paints map tiles.
    - The visible result is a blank, frozen map that will not load after zooming out or panning, plus heavy stutter.
    - Applying the configuration only once, after the style is fully loaded, breaks the loop AND makes the night theme
      take effect, so the map settles, shows the dark faded night style, and loads tiles normally.
  - Once the one-time configuration has run, the style handler does no further work on later style events.
  - Separately, the deck.gl overlay layers are rebuilt only when the auction data they depend on actually changes.
    - They depend on the slots, the auction log, the clearing results, the live bid arcs, and the pulses.
    - Moving the camera (panning or zooming) alone must not rebuild the overlay layers, so camera motion stays smooth.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - After the map's style first loads, the night-and-faded configuration is applied exactly one time, and subsequent
    style-update events apply it zero further times, so the style reaches its loaded state and tiles render.
  - Panning or zooming the map with unchanged auction data does not rebuild the deck.gl overlay layers.

- Make every :BillboardSlot: unmistakable on :LondonMapScene: and let the user rotate the camera freely.
  - Each slot is marked by a tall, bright vertical beam of light rising from its longitude and latitude.
    - The beam is clearly taller than the surrounding buildings so a slot is easy to spot from any angle or zoom.
    - The beam sits on top of a bright, pulsing glowing ring on the ground at the slot, so the exact spot reads clearly.
    - Before a slot clears the beam and ring use a vivid, high-contrast highlight colour; once a slot clears they switch
      to that slot's winning agent colour.
  - The primary slot layer keeps its existing layer identifier and exactly one entry per :BillboardSlot:.
    - The slot count and per-slot identity are unchanged; only the slot is drawn far more prominently than before.
  - The user can rotate and tilt the camera freely.
    - Dragging with the secondary (right) button or while holding a modifier key rotates and tilts the map.
    - Touch and trackpad rotate/pitch gestures are enabled too.
    - A navigation control with a compass sits in a corner that does not overlap the other panels; clicking its compass
      resets the bearing to north.
    - The camera bearing is part of the live view state, so rotation is reflected back into the scene.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - For an auction of 6 slots, the primary slot layer holds exactly 6 entries and each slot shows a tall highlight beam
    above a glowing ring at its longitude and latitude.
  - A navigation control with a compass is present, and rotating the camera updates the scene's bearing.

- Add a :MiniMap: overview to :LondonMapScene: so the user always knows where they are.
  - :MiniMap: is a small, flat, top-down 2D map inset in the top-right corner of the screen.
    - It shows the same centre as the main map but zoomed out to a neighbourhood-to-city overview, with no tilt.
    - A clear marker dot sits at the centre of :MiniMap: showing the user's current location on the main map.
    - When the main map's centre moves, :MiniMap: re-centres to match.
  - :MiniMap: is framed as a small glassmorphism card with rounded corners, matching the other floating panels.
  - :MiniMap: is for orientation only: it is not interactive and never steals gestures from the main map.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - :MiniMap: renders in the top-right corner as a small 2D top-down map with a centre marker.
  - When the main map centre changes, :MiniMap: re-centres to the same coordinates.

- Declutter the :AuctionHUD: so the round ticker is compact and readable, never a screen-filling list.
  - The :AuctionHUD: shows the round number and a one-line summary: how many slots are contested and the highest
    standing bid right now.
  - The standing-bid list is condensed.
    - It shows only the few highest standing bids (at most the top five), sorted by amount, with the rest summarised as
      a "+N more" line rather than listed.
    - Each row uses a short, readable slot label (a leading tag plus the last few digits of the id), not the full id.
    - The whole list sits in a fixed, modest maximum height and scrolls inside that height if needed; it never grows to
      fill the screen.
  - Agent budgets are shown compactly beneath the list.
  - The :AuctionHUD: sits on the right side, below :MiniMap:, and never overlaps it.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - With a round of 24 contested slots, the :AuctionHUD: lists at most five standing-bid rows plus a "+19 more" summary,
    and fits within its capped height instead of filling the screen.
  - The :AuctionHUD: still shows the round number, the highest standing bid, and every agent's remaining budget.

- Lighten the liquid glass on every floating panel so the map shows through more clearly.
  - Every glass panel — the control panel, :MiniMap: frame, :AuctionHUD:, and each :ScorecardPanel: — uses a fill
    opacity of about 20 percent (clearly more transparent than before).
  - The background blur is reduced to a lighter frost rather than a heavy blur, so the map detail behind stays crisp.
  - The hairline border, top sheen, rounded corners, and soft shadow stay; only the fill opacity and blur amount change.
  - Text stays high-contrast and fully legible over the lighter glass.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - The control panel, :MiniMap: frame, :AuctionHUD:, and a :ScorecardPanel: each render with an approximately
    20-percent-opacity fill and a lighter blur, while their content stays fully legible.

- Make the night and faded map theme apply reliably and stay applied on :LondonMapScene:.
  - The night light preset and faded theme are applied as soon as the map first loads.
  - After applying the configuration, the code reads the values back to confirm they actually took effect.
    - If the read-back does not yet show night and faded, the code applies the configuration again on the next map
      event, and keeps retrying ONLY until the read-back confirms night and faded are active, then stops permanently.
    - It also stops after a small fixed maximum number of attempts, so there is never an unbounded re-apply loop.
  - The code must not skip applying the configuration based only on the map's is-style-loaded flag.
    - That flag can stay false even when the configuration is settable, which would leave the map stuck on the bright
      default day theme — the exact bug this fixes.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - A short time after the map loads, reading back the active light preset gives night and the active theme gives faded.
  - Once night and faded are confirmed active, the configuration is not applied again (no endless re-apply).

- Centre the camera on :LondonMapScene: on the billboards as soon as they load, through the view state.
  - The first time :LondonMapScene: receives a non-empty set of :BillboardSlot: items (which happens when the user
    starts the auction), it updates the camera once to look at the billboards.
    - It sets the camera's centre longitude to the average of the slots' `lon` values and the centre latitude to the
      average of the slots' `lat` values.
    - It sets the zoom to a fixed overview level — about 14 — that shows the whole central-London cluster, and keeps the
      existing tilt so the billboards still read in 3D.
    - Only slots whose `lon` and `lat` are finite numbers are included in the averages; slots with missing or non-finite
      coordinates are skipped.
    - If no slot has finite `lon`/`lat`, the camera is left exactly as it is — it must never be set to a not-a-number
      coordinate, which would crash the map.
    - This billboard centring takes precedence over the geolocation centring whenever slots are present.
  - The camera is moved only through the same view state the map already uses — its centre longitude, centre latitude,
    and zoom — not through any separate map-instance method call.
  - The centring runs once per set of billboards, when they first appear — never on every render — so the user can pan,
    zoom, and rotate freely afterwards without the camera snapping back.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - When :LondonMapScene: first receives several billboards, the map's centre longitude and latitude become the average
    of the slots' positions and the zoom becomes the fixed overview level, with no not-a-number coordinate.
  - Re-rendering with that same set of billboards afterwards does not move the camera again.

- Show each :BillboardSlot: as a small ad-style billboard panel stuck to its building, not a tall beam.
  - The tall vertical light beam / pillar is removed entirely.
  - In its place each slot shows a small, bright, flat advertising panel — like a lit billboard screen mounted on the
    building at that spot.
    - The panel is compact, roughly building-height (it sits near rooftop level at the slot's `lon`/`lat`), and never
      taller than the surrounding buildings — it must read as a sign on a building, not a skyscraper-tall column.
    - The panel faces the camera so it stays readable from any rotation, tilt, or zoom.
    - The panel glows in a vivid highlight colour before the slot clears, then switches to the winning agent's colour
      once the slot clears.
  - A small, subtle glowing ring on the ground marks the exact spot, kept modest — not a large disk.
  - The primary slot layer keeps its existing layer identifier and exactly one entry per :BillboardSlot:.
    - The slot count and per-slot identity stay unchanged; only the shape of the marker changes.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - For an auction of 6 slots, the primary slot layer holds exactly 6 entries and each slot shows a small, camera-facing
    billboard panel near building height at its `lon`/`lat`, with no tall beam.

- Lay the agent scorecards out as a row along the bottom of the screen and group their repeated flagged actions.
  - The :ScorecardPanel: cards are arranged in a single horizontal row spread across the bottom of the screen.
    - One compact card per agent, evenly distributed across the width, instead of a tall vertical stack down one side.
    - The row sits over the map along the bottom edge; the map stays visible above it.
    - Each card has a fixed, modest height and never grows into a long internal scroll.
  - Within each card, repeated identical flagged actions (concession errors) are grouped rather than listed one by one.
    - Identical concession errors are collapsed into a single line carrying a count, for example "Premature Drop ×6".
    - This grouping is display-only; the money figures still come verbatim from the :AgentScorecard:.
  - Each card still shows surplusCaptured, overpayment, and leftOnTable, and click-to-explain still works on each figure.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - With four agents, exactly four :ScorecardPanel: cards render in a horizontal row along the bottom of the screen, not
    a vertical stack.
  - An agent with six identical premature-drop concession errors shows them as one grouped line with a count of six,
    rather than six separate repeated lines.

- Draw each :BillboardSlot: as a flat camera-facing billboard sign image, not a 3D cylinder or column.
  - The slot marker is rendered as a flat, image-based icon that always faces the camera (a billboard-style icon),
    positioned at the slot's `lon`/`lat` and lifted to roughly rooftop height so it reads as a sign on the building.
    - It must NOT be an extruded 3D column, cylinder, or solid shape — it is a flat, screen-like sign that turns to
      face the viewer at any rotation, tilt, or zoom.
    - The icon looks like a small bright advertising screen: a rounded rectangle with a vivid glowing fill and a thin
      bright border.
    - Its size is set in screen pixels and kept small and roughly constant, so it stays a readable sign and never grows
      into a giant object when zooming in.
    - It glows in a vivid highlight colour before the slot clears, then takes the winning agent's colour once the slot
      clears.
  - A small, subtle glowing ground ring still marks the exact spot, kept modest.
  - The primary slot layer keeps its existing layer identifier and exactly one entry per :BillboardSlot:, so the slot
    count and per-slot identity are unchanged.

  ***acceptance tests***
  - For an auction of 6 slots, the primary slot layer holds exactly 6 entries, each positioned at its slot's `lon`/`lat`
    and drawn as a flat camera-facing sign icon sized in screen pixels, with no extruded column or cylinder.
